ge of glucose as glycogen","Breakdown of glycogen to glucose"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of hepatic gluconeogenesis is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors\u003C/strong\u003E. This process is essential during fasting, starvation, or periods of prolonged exercise, when glucose availability is limited. The liver can synthesise glucose from substrates such as lactate, pyruvate, glycerol, and glucogenic amino acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakdown of glycogen to glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes glycogenolysis, a separate process from gluconeogenesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of glucose to fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes lipogenesis, which occurs when glucose is abundant\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of glucose as glycogen\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes glycogenesis, which occurs in the fed state\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation of fatty acids to produce glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - Fatty acids are an important source of energy in the fasting state, however they cannot be converted to produce glucose\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGluconeogenesis is particularly important during prolonged fasting when glycogen stores are depleted and glucose must be synthesised to maintain blood glucose levels, especially for glucose-dependent tissues like the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gluconeogenesis occurs primarily in the liver and produces glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors like amino acids and lactate.","The liver maintains blood glucose levels during fasting through gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis.","Key gluconeogenic precursors include pyruvate, lactate, glycerol, and glucogenic amino acids."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17353"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T18:05:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T18:05:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":